			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">If you read the WoW manual they admit that the "rested exp" that Mikara is talking about isn't meant to benefit people who play more than once or twice a week.  Basically, when you are in a "rested state" you gain exp faster than when you are in a "normal state".  The longer you stay logged out of the game the more rested your character becomes.  The longer you are in the game, or the more MOBs you kill, the more "normal" you become.  Every time you visit an Inn you become rested, but usually the minute you kill one MOB you are not rested any more.  If you log out for an evening, and come back the next day to play, your rested state might last 3 or 4 kills - then you'll be normal again.
<br />

<br />
Blizzard meant for it to be a way for people to catch back up with friends if they have to leave the game for a week or more at a time.  Being AFG for a week would build up a huge rested state which would allow you to kill MOBs for quite a while at double exp.  But it's not like being in a normal state makes you gain any less exp - just that in a rested state you gain a little more.
<br />

<br />
I remember once hearing that they actually planned an exp "penalty" for people who were logged into the game for long periods of time (to discourage "power-gamers" who play 24/7)... but IMO that would be a HUGE mistake.  I haven't seen anything to indicate that they implemented that.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
