			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well if you want to play with your friends you MUST all be the same side - Horde or Alliance.  The two sides cannot even communicate with one another in the early stages of the game.  It takes quite and effort to get to the neutral areas of the world, and even once you are there, you won't speak the same languages.
<br />

<br />
Horde charcaters cannot send tells or even do a /who for Alliance characters, and vice versa.  For all intents and purposes, you're not even playing the game together... until you get into the same zone!  Then it's usually a War!  <img src="images/smiles/icon_twisted.gif" alt="Twisted Evil" border="0" />   It a blast to be in one of the "fringe" zones when someone from the other side comes exploring in.
<br />

<br />
Now I don't know how much that changes at later stages in the game.  I'm still not even level 20 yet.  I've heard that later on there is a mingling of the two sides, but I've not seen it.
<br />

<br />
My recommendation is that if you all want to play together from the start - pick the same race.  Lets say you choose Alliance, but one of you is a Human and the others are Elfs and one is a Dwarf.  The journey from the Human area to the elf town is a long one and you run into some pretty tough stuff on the way.  I wouldn't recommend the trip to anyone under level 10 - unless you're planning to spend quite a lot of time on it and are willing to die a lot.
<br />

<br />
So bottome line - to play with friends the easiest thing to do right way is to all be the same race.  Later as you get the hang of the game you might be able to try different characters and run them together.
<br />

<br />
As for race/class balances... I haven't really played everything enough to try it out.  Each race gets some special abilities which lend themselves to certain classes or tradeskill.  For instance, Taurens get improved Herbalism, if they chose to go theat tradeskill path. (Herbalism is a gathersing skill that is used in conjunction with Alchemy)  I think Dwarves get  abonus to Mining (another gathering skill that is best suited for being used with Blacksmithing or Engineering)   Gnomes get bonuses to Engineering... stuff like that.
<br />

<br />
Popular combos seem to be:
<br />

<br />
Hunters - Night Elf, Dwarf or Tauren
<br />
Shaman/Druid - Tauren or Night Elf (Night Elf is the only Alliance race that can be these)
<br />
Warriors - Human, Dwarven, Orc, Tauren
<br />
Wizards/Warlocks - Undead, Gnomes
<br />
Priests - Humans, Elfs, Undead
<br />

<br />
Like I said, I haven't played them all so I don't know.  I played a Tauren Shaman a lot - I like the Taurens the most - but he's on another server so I kinda abandoned him.  I remade a new Tauren that is still low level, but this one's a Druid. (WoW druids are not like EQ Druids - they are a little more melee oriented - think Diablo II Druids...)  I also have a Human Pally that I like a lot.  I started a Night Elf Hunter that isn't bad.  And I made an Orc Warrior that I just haven't had time to mess with.
<br />

<br />
It's all spelled out pretty well in the manual that comes with the game.  It's worth taking 10 mintues to read thru it quickly to get a good idea what you want to do with your character.  Or I'm sure if you wannt get a feel for it before your game arrives you can probably read up on all the races, classes, and tradeskills on the WoW web site.
<br />

<br />
It also helps to do something useful to your character - it wouldn't pay to be a Blacksmith if you are a Druid since druids can't wear anything more than Leather armor until 40th level...  You want a tradeskill that is usefull to you because you WILL be able to make very nice items right off the bat that are as good or better than stuff oyu will find while hunting.  And the stuff off the merchants is so high priced you won't be able to afford that at first.  So you'll probably end up making most of what you wear early on.
<br />

<br />
the only drawback I've found is that you can only have two tradeskills/gathering skills at one time.  If you want to get a different skill you have to unlearn one of your old ones, and if you unlearn it your skill is erased - so you'd have to start all over at zero again if you took it back up.  So most people take a gathering skill first to compliment the tradeskill they choose.  Like Leatherworkers take the Skinning skill, Miners will either go Blacksmithing or Engineering, Herbalists go Alchemy or maybe Enchanting.  There's nothing that says you can't be a Blacksmith and a Alchemist... you just wouldn't have any gathering abliltiy to get the raw materials for yourself - you'd have to buy them from other players.
<br />

<br />
That's the Long answer to your question!  <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="Razz" border="0" />   Can't wait to cya in game Goth!  Remember - Central Time Zone - Alleria Server!</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
